{"id":"1502.07115","submitter":"Davide Marenduzzo","authors":"E. Tjhung, A. Tiribocchi, D. Marenduzzo, M. E. Cates","title":"A minimal physical model captures the shapes of crawling cells","comments":"37 pages, 11 figures, 1 table","journal-ref":"Nat. Comm. 6, 5420 (2015)","doi":"10.1038/ncomms6420","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.soft physics.bio-ph q-bio.CB","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Cell motility in higher organisms (eukaryotes) is crucial to biological\nfunctions ranging from wound healing to immune response, and also implicated in\ndiseases such as cancer. For cells crawling on hard surfaces, significant\ninsights into motility have been gained from experiments replicating such\nmotion in vitro. Such experiments show that crawling uses a combination of\nactin treadmilling (polymerization), which pushes the front of a cell forward,\nand myosin-induced stress (contractility), which retracts the rear. Here we\npresent a simplified physical model of a crawling cell, consisting of a droplet\nof active polar fluid with contractility throughout, but treadmilling connected\nto a thin layer near the supporting wall. The model shows a variety of shapes\nand/or motility regimes, some closely resembling cases seen experimentally. Our\nwork strongly supports the view that cellular motility exploits autonomous\nphysical mechanisms whose operation does not need continuous regulatory effort.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 25 Feb 2015 10:33:17 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-24"}
